snippet.title: TED-Ed
snippet.description:
TED-Ed’s commitment to creating lessons worth sharing is an extension of TED’s mission of spreading great ideas. Within TED-Ed’s growing library of TED-Ed animations, you will find carefully curated educational videos, many of which represent collaborations between talented educators and animators nominated through the TED-Ed website (ed.ted.com).

Want to suggest an idea for a TED-Ed animation or get involved with TED-Ed? Visit our website at: http://ed.ted.com/get_involved.

Also, consider donating to us on Patreon! By doing so, you directly support our mission and receive some pretty awesome rewards: https://www.patreon.com/teded

For more information on using TED for commercial purposes (e.g. employee learning, in a film, or in an online course), please submit a Media Request using this link: https://media-requests.ted.com/

snippet.title: The philosophy of Stoicism - Massimo Pigliucci
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-philosophy-of-stoicism-massimo-pigliucci

What is the best life we can live? How can we cope with whatever the universe throws at us and keep thriving nonetheless? The ancient Greco-Roman philosophy of Stoicism explains that while we may not always have control over the events affecting us, we can have control over how we approach things. Massimo Pigliucci describes the philosophy of Stoicism. 

Lesson by Massimo Pigliucci, animation by Compote Collective.

The earliest time measurements were observations of cycles of the natural world, using patterns of changes from day to night and season to season to build calendars. More precise time-keeping eventually came along to put time in more convenient boxes. But what exactly are we measuring? Andrew Zimmerman Jones contemplates whether time is something that physically exists or is just in our heads.

snippet.title: The tragic myth of Orpheus and Eurydice - Brendan Pelsue
snippet.description:
Check out our Patreon page: https://www.patreon.com/teded

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-tragic-myth-of-orpheus-and-eurydice-brendan-pelsue

The marriage of Orpheus, the greatest of all poets and musicians, to Eurydice, a wood nymph, was heralded as the perfect union. Anyone could tell the couple was deeply in love. So when their wedding ceremony ended in Eurydice's untimely death, Orpheus had no choice but to venture into the underworld to try to reclaim his lost love. Brendan Pelsue shares the tragic myth of Orpheus and Eurydice.

Lesson by Brendan Pelsue, animation by Anton Bogaty.

snippet.title: How does the stock market work? - Oliver Elfenbaum
snippet.description:
Download a free audiobook version of "The Richest Man in Babylon" and support TED-Ed's nonprofit mission: https://www.audible.com/ted-ed

Check out our full book recommendation: https://shop.ed.ted.com/products/the-richest-man-in-babylon

--

In the 1600s, the Dutch East India Company employed hundreds of ships to trade goods around the globe. In order to fund their voyages, the company turned to private citizens to invest money to support trips in exchange for a share of the profits. In doing so, they unknowingly invented the world’s first stock market. So how do companies and investors use the market today? Oliver Elfenbaum explains.

Lesson by Oliver Elfenbaum, directed by Tom Gran & Madeleine Grossi.

snippet.title: What makes something "Kafkaesque"? - Noah Tavlin
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/what-makes-something-kafkaesque-noah-tavlin

 The term Kafkaesque has entered the vernacular to describe unnecessarily complicated and frustrating experiences, especially with bureaucracy. But does standing in a long line to fill out confusing paperwork really capture the richness of Kafka’s vision? Beyond the word’s casual use, what makes something "Kafkaesque"? Noah Tavlin explains. 

Lesson by Noah Tavlin, animation by TED-Ed.

snippet.title: What really happened during the Salem Witch Trials - Brian A. Pavlac
snippet.description:
Dig into how the infamous Salem Witch Trials began and why they remain a cautionary tale of the dangers of groupthink and scapegoating.

--

You’ve been accused of a crime you did not commit. It’s impossible to prove your innocence. If you insist that you’re innocent anyway, you’ll likely be found guilty and executed. But if you confess, apologize, and implicate others, you’ll go free. This was the choice facing those accused of witchcraft in Salem, Massachusetts in the 17th century. How did this happen? Brian A. Pavlac investigates.

Lesson by Brian A. Pavlac, directed by Lucy Animation Studio.

snippet.title: The psychology of narcissism - W. Keith Campbell
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-psychology-of-narcissism-w-keith-campbell

Narcissism isn’t just a personality type that shows up in advice columns; it’s actually a set of traits classified and studied by psychologists. But what causes it? And can narcissists improve on their negative traits? W. Keith Campbell describes the psychology behind the elevated and sometimes detrimental self-involvement of narcissists. 

Lesson by W. Keith Campbell, animation by TOGETHER.

snippet.title: What makes muscles grow? - Jeffrey Siegel
snippet.description:
View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/what-makes-muscles-grow-jeffrey-siegel

We have over 600 muscles in our bodies that help bind us together, hold us up, and help us move. Your muscles also need your constant attention, because the way you treat them on a daily basis determines whether they will wither or grow. Jeffrey Siegel illustrates how a good mix of sleep, nutrition and exercise keep your muscles as big and strong as possible. 

Lesson by Jeffrey Siegel, animation by Brett Underhill.

snippet.title: Why sitting is bad for you - Murat Dalkilinç
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/why-sitting-is-bad-for-you-murat-dalkilinc

Sitting down for brief periods can help us recover from stress or recuperate from exercise. But nowadays, our lifestyles make us sit much more than we move around. Are our bodies built for such a sedentary existence? Murat Dalkilinç investigates the hidden risks of sitting down. 

Lesson by Murat Dalkilinç, animation by Oxbow Creative.

snippet.title: How Thor got his hammer - Scott A. Mellor
snippet.description:
Sign up for our newsletter and never miss an animation: http://bit.ly/TEDEdNewsletter

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/how-thor-got-his-hammer-scott-a-mellor

Loki the mischief-maker, writhes in Thor’s iron grip. The previous night, he’d snuck up on Thor’s wife and shorn off her beautiful hair. To fix what he’d done, Loki rushes to the dwarves and tricks them into making gifts for the gods. Wanting to best their smith rivals, the dwarves make a set of golden treasures, including a hammer called Mjolnir. Scott A. Mellor traces the legend of Thor’s hammer.

Lesson by Scott A. Mellor, directed by Remus and Kiki.

snippet.title: The myth of Pandora’s box - Iseult Gillespie
snippet.description:
Find out how students can share their ideas as TED Talks here: http://bit.ly/2zpAQUc

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-myth-of-pandora-s-box-iseult-gillespie

Pandora was the first mortal woman, breathed into being by Hephaestus, god of fire. The gods gave her gifts of language, craftsmanship and emotion. From Zeus she received two gifts: the trait of curiosity and a heavy box screwed tightly shut -- never to be opened. But what treasure could never be seen by human eyes, and why was it in her care? Iseult Gillespie explores the mystery of Pandora’s box.

localized.title: The myth of Pandora’s box - Iseult Gillespie
localized.description:

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-myth-of-pandora-s-box-iseult-gillespie

Pandora was the first mortal woman, breathed into being by Hephaestus, god of fire. The gods gave her gifts of language, craftsmanship and emotion. From Zeus she received two gifts: the trait of curiosity and a heavy box screwed tightly shut -- never to be opened. But what treasure could never be seen by human eyes, and why was it in her care? Iseult Gillespie explores the mystery of Pandora’s box.

snippet.title: The tale of the doctor who defied Death - Iseult Gillespie
snippet.description:
Dive into the German tale of Godfather Death and his godson, the doctor who tries to master mortality.

--

A husband and wife were in despair. The woman had just given birth to their 13th child, and the growing family was quickly running out of food and money. Wandering into the woods, the father encountered a skeletal figure with sunken eyes and a gaunt face: this was Death himself, come to offer his services as Godfather. Iseult Gillespie tells the tale of Death and the doctor.

snippet.title: A brief history of chess - Alex Gendler
snippet.description:
Trace the storied history of the game of chess, from its origins in 7th century India to the computer software we use today. 

--

The attacking infantry advances, their elephants already having broken the defensive line. The king tries to retreat, but the enemy flanks him from the rear. Escape is impossible. This isn’t a real war— nor is it just a game. Over the 1,500 years of its existence, chess has been known as a military strategy tool, a metaphor for human affairs and a measure of genius. Alex Gendler shares its history.

Lesson by Alex Gendler, directed by Remus & Kiki.

snippet.title: Why incompetent people think they're amazing - David Dunning
snippet.description:
Check out our Patreon page: https://www.patreon.com/teded

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/why-incompetent-people-think-they-re-amazing-david-dunning

How good are you with money? What about reading people’s emotions? How healthy are you, compared to other people you know? Knowing how our skills stack up against others is useful in many ways. But psychological research suggests that we’re not very good at evaluating ourselves accurately. In fact, we frequently overestimate our own abilities. David Dunning describes the Dunning-Kruger effect. 

Lesson by David Dunning, directed by Wednesday Studio, music and sound by Tom Drew.

snippet.title: How to spot a pyramid scheme - Stacie Bosley
snippet.description:
Learn the techniques and tricks that pyramid schemes use to recruit new members and how to avoid being fooled yourself. 

--

In 2004, a nutrition company offered a life-changing opportunity to earn a full-time income for part-time work. There were only two steps to get started: purchase a $500 kit and recruit two more members. By 2013, the company was making $200 million. There was just one problem -- the vast majority of members earned less than they paid in. Stacie Bosley explains what a pyramid scheme is and how to spot one.

Lesson by Stacie Bosley, directed by Wooden Plane Productions.

snippet.title: Why do people join cults? - Janja Lalich
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/why-do-people-join-cults-janja-lalich

Today, there are thousands of cults around the world. Broadly speaking, a cult is a group or movement with a shared commitment to a usually extreme ideology that’s typically embodied in a charismatic leader. But what exactly differentiates cults from other groups – and why do people join them? Janja Lalich describes how cults recruit and manipulate their members.

snippet.title: The myth of Cupid and Psyche - Brendan Pelsue
snippet.description:
Check out TED-Ed's Patreon page! https://www.patreon.com/teded

View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/the-myth-of-cupid-and-psyche-brendan-pelsue

Psyche was born so beautiful that she was worshipped as a new incarnation of Venus, the goddess of love. But human lovers were too intimidated to approach her, and Apollo recommended her father abandon her on a crag where she would marry “a cruel and savage, serpent-like winged evil.” But Psyche’s story ended up being much more interesting. Brendan Pelsue shares the myth of Cupid and Psyche.

Lesson by Brendan Pelsue, directed by TED-Ed.

snippet.title: Debunking the myths of OCD - Natascha M. Santos
snippet.description:
View full lesson: http://ed.ted.com/lessons/debunking-the-myths-of-ocd-natascha-m-santos

There’s a common misconception that if you like to meticulously organize your things, keep your hands clean, or plan out your weekend to the last detail, you might be OCD. In fact, OCD (Obsessive Compulsive Disorder) is a serious psychiatric condition that is frequently misunderstood by society and mental health professionals alike. Natascha M. Santos debunks the myths surrounding OCD.

Lesson by Natascha M. Santos, animation by Zedem Media.

snippet.title: What is imposter syndrome and how can you combat it? - Elizabeth Cox
snippet.description:
View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/what-is-imposter-syndrome-and-how-can-you-combat-it-elizabeth-cox

Check out our Patreon page: https://www.patreon.com/teded

Even after writing eleven books and winning several awards, Maya Angelou couldn’t escape the doubt that she hadn’t earned her accomplishments. This feeling of fraudulence is extremely common. Why can’t so many of us shake feelings that our ideas and skills aren’t worthy of others’ attention? Elizabeth Cox describes the psychology behind the imposter syndrome, and what you can do to combat it.

localized.title: What is imposter syndrome and how can you combat it? - Elizabeth Cox
localized.description:
View full lesson: https://ed.ted.com/lessons/what-is-imposter-syndrome-and-how-can-you-combat-it-elizabeth-cox

Check out our Patreon page: https://www.patreon.com/teded

Even after writing eleven books and winning several awards, Maya Angelou couldn’t escape the doubt that she hadn’t earned her accomplishments. This feeling of fraudulence is extremely common. Why can’t so many of us shake feelings that our ideas and skills aren’t worthy of others’ attention? Elizabeth Cox describes the psychology behind the imposter syndrome, and what you can do to combat it.

Lesson by Elizabeth Cox, directed by Sharon Colman.

Has anyone ever told you, “Stand up straight!” or scolded you for slouching at a family dinner? Comments like that might be annoying—but they’re not wrong. Your posture is the foundation for every movement your body makes and can determine how well your body adapts to the stresses on it. Murat Dalkilinç gives the pros of good posture.

snippet.title: A brief history of dogs - David Ian Howe
snippet.description:
Trace the history of how wolves, one of humanity’s oldest rivals, evolved into the domesticated dogs we call “man’s best friend.”

--

Since their emergence over 200,000 years ago, modern humans have established communities all over the planet. But they didn’t do it alone. Whatever corner of the globe you find humans in today, you’re likely to find another species as well: dogs. So how did one of our oldest rivals, the wolf, evolve into man’s best friend? David Ian Howe traces the history of humanity’s first domesticated animal. 

Lesson by David Ian Howe, directed by Cabong Studios.

snippet.textDisplay:
How to properly order your Starbucks drinks:
1. size
2. hot or iced
3. Type of drink
4. Any modifications
Example: May I please have a Venti Iced Carmel macchiato, also with no drizzle and made with almond milk. Thank you.

I’m a Starbucks barista and if more people ordered like this, it would make our jobs so much easier!! Thanks!!


When you say a triple shot almond milk 2 pump hazelnut iced macchiato in a grande cup.... it’s much more difficult to enter in our system because you listed it in the opposite way we need to enter it in (write it down)

snippet.textDisplay: It’s so crazy to see you all grown up! I am too, but like I remember being 14 watching your fall hot chocolate videos wearing stuff from forever 21 and just vibing at home w/ my parents. Now I’m 22, trying to move out of my parents house & go move across the country with my boyfriend and become my own business woman. I miss you girl, I wish we could be friends in real life & catch up because you literally feel like a long lost friend. Thanks for your vulnerability and honesty now as an adult! You helped me through a lot as a teen and it’s nice to see your face again 💖💖💖stronger than ever. Proud of you!

snippet.textDisplay:
https://youtu.be/32Lf8r-gZeY
The first video in a series on the Philosophical Battle of the Titans - Kant vs. Hegel. Here we compare and contrast the logic of Aristotle with that of Hegel, displaying the differences between the reasoning strategies of traditional logic and Hegel's narrative process-reasoning. I flesh out my claims that Hegel's influence is pervasive despite his obscurity, that his Logic IS his metaphysics, and that the danger in Hegelian philosophy results more from his historical acolytes than from Hegel himself, though Hegel's arrogation of a God's-eye-position was the explicit proverbial "first step" on the slippery slope down which Western thought has "progressed" (yes, I mean that ironically) over the past two centuries.

snippet.textDisplay: Okay. The arrow of time is split up into 3 parts. The physiological, thermodynamic (explained in the video) and the cosmological arrow of time. The physiological arrow of time is the way organisms perceive time, remembering the past and not knowing the future. The thermodynamic arrow of time is disorder increasing after any events, and the cosmological arrow of time is the universe expanding over time. There is a reason why time is moving only in one direction - forward. This is because time is the 4th dimension that we can not understand (due to being in the 3rd dimension, and higher dimensions can not be visualized or controlled) and therefore is unchangeable by us, and is instead a set property, only moving in one direction. The dilation of time, and time makes no logical sense to us, the same way that a 3d object will make no sense to a 2d organism, yet in both cases they can be approximated to fit observations. This may reason why there is only one direction of time, but does not explain why it moves forward. This can be explained in the anthropic principle - time must be moving forward or else we (intelligent life) could not possible exist. This is because the thermodynamic arrow of time must be moving forward to allow the release of energy through respiration and other processes. If it were moving backward, we would have to be moving into more order, and therefore wouldn't be able to do any irreversible actions, not even being able to move. There may be some parallel universe where the universe is contracting and entropy is inverted like tenet, but no life would be sustained. Therefore time can only move forward, for us to exist. And any situation which we do not exist in are irrelevant because we can not make any logical observations, and therefore no relevant theories. Time is a property not only a property of our universe, but is an entire dimension which governs all observations and allows life to live.

snippet.textDisplay:
An American spy goes to the KGB to defect. He goes up to the receptionist and says, "I'm an American spy and I wish to surrender."
"Go to Room 5."
He goes to Room 5. "I'm an American spy and I wish to surrender."
"Do you have a weapon?"
"Yes."
"Then you need to go to Room 20."
He goes to Room 20. "I'm an American spy, I wish to surrender, and I have a weapon."
"But do you have a communication device?"
"Yes."
"Then what are you doing here? Go to Room 11!"
He goes to Room 11. "I'm an American spy, I wish to surrender, I have a weapon and a communication device."
"Do you have an assignment?"
"Yes."
"Then go do it, and stop bothering other people who are working!"

snippet.textDisplay: , I find the garden variety narcissist quite fun and enjoyable to be around in the right circumstances. Sometimes they make great planners and leaders if the traits are not too high. And if they are your “friend,” and it suits them, you can count on them to be the bigger bully if you’re being screwed with. They can be very financially successful in high paying fields, such as politics and entertainment (let’s admit it, no way around it, having financial health and money to buy things in our capitalistic culture is a happiness producing variable). Sometimes they’re just utterly self-absorbed lecturers (and difficult to differentiate from spectrum issues). If you are a sensitive person with healthy parental bonding/attachment, you will be very disappointed being in a romantic relationship with this kind of person. They will never deliver the goods, because they can’t; you’ll never get your basic emotional needs met, and more or less will have to deal with the obvious infuriating behaviors—stonewalling, gas-lighting, guilt-tripping and other defensive strategies. Sometimes narcissists with about the same level of narcissism can be in long term relationships with about the same amount of conflict, unhappiness etc. as non-narcissist partners.

snippet.textDisplay:
"Understanding the Significance of Pandora's Box"
By N.S. Gill
A "Pandora's box" is a metaphor in our modern languages, and the proverbial phrase refers to a source of endless complications or trouble arising from a single, simple miscalculation. Pandora's story comes to us from ancient Greek mythology, specifically a set of epic poems by Hesiod, called the Theogony and Works and Days. Written during the 7th century BC, these poems relate how the gods came to create Pandora and how the gift Zeus gave her ultimately ends the Golden Age of humankind.
https://www.thoughtco.com/what-was-pandoras-box-118577

snippet.textDisplay:
Hi just a question I wanted to ask others (no need to answer if you don’t want to or if you can’t think of an answer) (in this question, let’s say the afterlife exists, but I won’t say exactly what happens in the afterlife):

If you had the choice, would you live one life and move to the afterlife after dying, or would you prefer to be reincarnated multiple times before going to the afterlife? (You’d be reincarnated with some of your memories from the previous life, but how much you remember is random. There is also a limit to how many times you’d be reincarnated. In this version, let’s say you get 10 more lives)

Also, once you move to the afterlife, you’ll recall all of your memories from your life. If you were reincarnated, you’d remember everything from all of your lives.

I just want to know what other people think about this and there reasons for picking what they chose. 😊

snippet.textDisplay: Are you kidding, talking about Soviet domination broken by deep blue, not mentioning Bobby Fischer? He was the single most important figure in the history of chess. His rivalry and World Championship match against Boris Spassky was turned into cold war propaganda, which popularized the game on both sides of the Iron Curtain. Before Fischer, there were a handful of professional players all over the world (in the sense that they made a living only by playing chess).

snippet.textDisplay: 1:20 88% of Americans rate themselves as having above average driving skills: this could actually be correct! People often dont understand the difference between an average and a median. Its perfectly possible to have 88% or people to be above average (lets say by a metric such as accidents per 10,000 miles). IF the remaining 12% of driver cause way more accidents, they drag down the average. Simple example: if 99 drivers never cause an accident, and 1 driver causes ALL accidents, then 99% of drivers drive accident free above average. EG: dont ask for an average if you actually want to know the median, such as when ranking people.

snippet.textDisplay: The trouble with the examples of "performance" in software engineering and driving is that they are both extremely subjective matters. How does one objectively measure performance in software engineering? Lines of code written per unit of time? Functionality developed per unit of time? Some software engineers will produce many lines of code quickly but those lines will be superfluous, redundant, bug-riddled, non-functional, misleading, and difficult to read. Some software engineers will add lots of functionality quickly, but perhaps introduce many more bugs and vulnerabilities and inhibit scalability when compared to the work of other software engineers that add functionality slower. Driving is the same way; There are obviously preferences and styles when it comes to driving. Some value speed, some precision, some safety. How would you weigh the value of each (and more aspects of driving I surely have missed) in a way that can measure collective driving capability and skill? It would make sense that drivers and ESPECIALLY software engineers would consider themselves in the top 10-5% and this is because according to their definition of what it means to be a good driver or a good software engineer, they ARE in that top 5-10%. There are much better examples of the Dunning-Kruger effect and those examples are when people are just objectively wrong on major points of a subject matter while believing they are correct because they have some (limited) knowledge on the subject. A great example would be the origin of humans. A not-particularly-educated person might believe an idea on the matter that has very little support other than what was taught by some religion, but this same person would think they absolutely know the truth. Then imagine a legitimate expert on the matter of human origins, such as a bonafide biologist with some legitimate geneticist and archaeologist experience, who admits that they leave room to change their mind/position on the matter of what they believe about the origins of humans, should new and better evidence be presented to them.

snippet.textDisplay:
The only progress is made by people who act above expectations. Otherwise there would be no progress. If everyone knew exactly what they could, and could not, do, then there would be no progress.

It Couldn’t Be Done
By Edgar Albert Guest

Somebody said that it couldn’t be done
But he with a chuckle replied
That “maybe it couldn’t,” but he would be one
Who wouldn’t say so till he’d tried.
So he buckled right in with the trace of a grin
On his face. If he worried he hid it.
He started to sing as he tackled the thing
That couldn’t be done, and he did it!

Somebody scoffed: “Oh, you’ll never do that;
At least no one ever has done it;”
But he took off his coat and he took off his hat
And the first thing we knew he’d begun it.
With a lift of his chin and a bit of a grin,
Without any doubting or quiddit,
He started to sing as he tackled the thing
That couldn’t be done, and he did it.

There are thousands to tell you it cannot be done,
There are thousands to prophesy failure,
There are thousands to point out to you one by one,
The dangers that wait to assail you.
But just buckle in with a bit of a grin,
Just take off your coat and go to it;
Just start in to sing as you tackle the thing
That “cannot be done,” and you’ll do it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Psyche pronounced Psichí ‘’ch’’ is the Greek letter Χ that sound like h in the word home
So, is not ‘’s-a-i-k-i’’ is Ψυχή > Psichí
Ψυχή means soul in Greek

Since this is a Greek myth it should be appropriate to use the original Greek names of the Gods and not the Roman equivalents!
Everyone knows the Roman translations but in reality their religion came from Ancient Greece

Psyche is Ψυχή (psichí)
Venus is Αφροδίτη (Aphrodite)
Cupid is Έρως (Èros)
Proserpine is Περσεφόνη (Persefóni)
Pleasure is Ηδονή (Idoní)

snippet.textDisplay:
It's a physically and mentally exhausting condition to have. I suffer from obsessions about harming others, or doing something shameful and then compulsively seek reassurance from my close family and friends to neutralise the worry.

It's also extremely frustrating when people close to me claim to have OCD because they like to keep their desk in order.

If they knew that I once spent an evening worrying that I caused an earthquake thousands of miles away by treading on the pavement too hard on the street outside my house (crazy I know, but that is an example an obsession I had when the Italian earthquake happened in 2009!) then they might have a greater understanding of what OCD really is.

snippet.textDisplay:
Since I was little I was aware that I had OCD, but I wasn't fully aware of what it caused or how it truly affects the lives of those who have it. I simply knew that it was hecka inconvenient to have to walk backwards and flip the light switches so many times and repeat everything I say and bump into so many tables to keep the symmetry (like the left side of my stomach is hit and so I've gotta hit the right side with the same amount of force and in the same spot) and everything else that I have to do. I started working on it on my own and got a lot better about it, and therefore the inconvenience level was low (like instead of repeating everything out loud I could say it again in my head and be fine, and it got to the point where I no longer need to do it anymore), although it's slowly been raising the past couple years and a recent breakup that I had (5 months ago) triggered it in a sort of way that makes it to where I now have to write out certain words that I say with my finger in different ways (cursive and print, although now I can choose instead of having to do both) and a lot of the things I had gotten better about have gotten a lot worse.
I realized a couple years ago that it isn't something to joke about, it isn't something to take lightly, it isn't something that can be fixed by just not doing it anymore; it's truly an obsession that controls your mind and really hurts to try and stop.
For me, it's gotten so bad that I have woken in the middle of the night from dreams after doing something the "right" way (aka listening to my OCD), then forcing myself to go back and do it the "wrong" way just to see what would happen, and then due to the anxiety I was feeling getting stuck in that loop of doing it the wrong way and not being able to do it the right way because the anxiety was too much and I couldn't think straight (that really sucked).
Anyways, sorry for how long this is, I just have so much to say about it and no one to say it to😌

snippet.textDisplay:
What a great video.
I have been watching and reading many things related to OCD lately.
I had been diagnosed with OCD at 12, after a year spending (or wasting time) with my obsessions and compulsions. I don't know how I did but I overcome the OCD at 18.

Now, with all this covid-19 situation, I am struggling again with all those obsessions trying to not go to the compulsive side of myself.

Even if we think we are done with this illness, we are never very sure about it and have to keep fighting against it.

But we can do it!

snippet.textDisplay:
I was always considered "weird" by others because of my strange habits and because I enjoyed solitude, but I never thought that I had OCD, until I was driven mad by my actions and habits so I had to consider it.
Ever since I was a little kid, I had many habits and some of them include:
Washing hands several times because of my great fear of germs, opening and closing doors multiple times until it feels right, checking things 10-20 times just to be safe, looking under a plate before eating from it(or under a cup before drinking from it), arranging things in order alphabeticaly, by color or by size, repeating words or actions until it feels correct, making things stand straight under the perfect angle, obssesion with symmetry, intrusive and repetitive thoughts, obsession with perfection, walking on the edge of the sidewalk or following a line, walking on cracks or avoiding cracks on the street, stepping on other people's shadows, performing weird quick motions with my hands for a temporary relief... I also get anxious if I cannot finish a sentence or a word, and if somebody throws away some of my possesions, even if it's small and useless, I still like keeping everything I own. OCD is extremely annoying, exhausting and time-consuming, so please don't joke about it. Also, thank you if you read this far.

snippet.textDisplay: Guys, PLEASE don’t take this lightly I didn’t think it was that big a deal but just over a week ago, I woke up with a piercing pain in my shoulder and neck and could barely move. I was scared that I was gonna be disabled for life but I managed to recover. This was definitely a life-changing warning and I won’t dare to take my posture lightly again. Anyone who is reading this, make sure u are exercising regularly, stretching before workouts, living healthy, and have a good posture. Stay safe <3
